00:01:38.031 --> 00:01:39.114
HERSHEY FELDER: Thank you.

00:01:39.114 --> 00:01:41.026
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:43.894 --> 00:01:47.430
To be more specific [AUDIO OUT]
break my own record.

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:50.040
It's good to know that
Beethoven broke Irving Berlin's

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:51.010
record actually.

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:52.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:56.490
I'm just a vehicle for doing
this stuff and telling stories.

00:01:56.490 --> 00:01:58.290
A lot of this is
both talking to you

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:01.290
in music-- which is what
I do actually in reality.

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:05.220
It's creating character as
well as playing the music

00:02:05.220 --> 00:02:07.890
and looking very
carefully at the music

00:02:07.890 --> 00:02:09.720
as we create the character.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:14.070
When I started this, probably
25 years ago, people simply

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:14.770
laughed at me.

00:02:14.770 --> 00:02:15.960
They said, nobody
is going to come.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:17.050
Nobody knows who you are.

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:18.580
Nobody cares.

00:02:18.580 --> 00:02:20.950
And I wanted to start
with Chopin above all.

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:23.259
So people said, well
"Chop-in"-- who knows "Chop-in?"

00:02:23.259 --> 00:02:25.050
And you want to call
it Monsieur "Chop-in."

00:02:25.050 --> 00:02:26.700
So nobody's going
to know anything.

00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:28.110
Nobody recognizes your name.

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:29.966
What's a Hershey Felder?

00:02:29.966 --> 00:02:31.590
Why don't you start
with somebody who's

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:33.240
a little bit more recognizable?

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.801
At this point, I met members
of the Gershwin family.

00:02:35.801 --> 00:02:37.800
And I said, well, I play
"The Rhapsody in Blue."

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.710
Why don't I create the role of
George Gershwin, just as a fun

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:41.420
thing.

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:44.220
And somebody in Hollywood
said, pull back your hair.

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:44.725
So I did.

00:02:44.725 --> 00:02:45.350
They said, gee.

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:46.470
You've got the same nose.

00:02:46.470 --> 00:02:47.630
I said, [AUDIO OUT].

00:02:47.630 --> 00:02:50.420
It travels well.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:52.560
So I created the character
of George Gershwin.

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:54.930
And all of a sudden,
this whole idea took off.

00:02:54.930 --> 00:02:56.670
It's become a bit of
a cottage industry,

00:02:56.670 --> 00:02:58.360
but a little more than that.

00:02:58.360 --> 00:02:59.360
So the idea is, really--

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.443
one of the things that's
wonderful about this kind

00:03:01.443 --> 00:03:03.480
of stuff is that I get
to engage audience.

00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:05.900
And I've engaged audience
anywhere from 18,000

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:08.760
at Ravinia in Chicago, where
I talked to them directly

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:11.220
and they ask questions,
to a small audience,

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:15.876
like we have today, a nice, very
esoteric, thoughtful audience,

00:03:15.876 --> 00:03:17.750
everybody with their
computers in their laps.

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:18.249
It's just--

00:03:18.249 --> 00:03:19.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:21.690
Which brings me to this
gentleman's question.

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:22.800
So [AUDIO OUT].

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:23.480
AUDIENCE: John.

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:23.770
HERSHEY FELDER: John.

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:26.610
And tell me what happened, John,
for the rest of the crowd here.

00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:27.565
And I'll repeat for--

00:03:27.565 --> 00:03:29.440
AUDIENCE: I was at your
performance, I think,

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:30.300
two Thursdays ago.

00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:33.746
And we found out later,
a PG&amp;E transformer blew.

00:03:33.746 --> 00:03:35.390
And the whole theater went dark.

00:03:35.390 --> 00:03:35.890
And--

00:03:35.890 --> 00:03:38.010
HERSHEY FELDER: It was the most
exciting night in the theater.

00:03:38.010 --> 00:03:40.890
So there I am, 20 minutes into
this show-- and this gentleman

00:03:40.890 --> 00:03:41.910
says, I was there.

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:42.940
Has that ever happened?

00:03:42.940 --> 00:03:45.810
So let me just preface this
by saying, you'd think,

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:48.540
in Mountain View, the technology
would always be working.

00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:51.420
And apparently, not the case.

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:52.580
So there I was on stage.

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:54.270
There were 600
people in the house.

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:55.230
John was one of them.

00:03:55.230 --> 00:03:57.150
I begin the
"Beethoven" show, which

00:03:57.150 --> 00:03:59.580
begins very derelictly
with Beethoven's very

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:00.430
first composition.

00:04:00.430 --> 00:04:04.260
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "9
VARIATIONS IN C MINOR"]

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:06.420
Imagine, he was 11-years-old.

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:15.630
And even then, he
had a sense of hope.

00:04:22.670 --> 00:04:26.090
And then, I get to
some fancy part.

00:04:26.090 --> 00:04:28.250
Blackout!

00:04:28.250 --> 00:04:30.030
And I said, this
is very effective.

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:31.340
But it wasn't just a blackout.

00:04:31.340 --> 00:04:32.270
It was a bang.

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:33.140
It was a pop.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:34.600
All of a sudden, lights went.

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:35.530
Sound went.

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:36.830
And black.

00:04:36.830 --> 00:04:38.270
And 600 people sat there.

00:04:38.270 --> 00:04:40.670
And I said, OK, now what?

00:04:40.670 --> 00:04:42.200
And so, clearly,
the mics were off.

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:44.060
The electricity was gone.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:46.190
And I said, ladies
and gentlemen, this

00:04:46.190 --> 00:04:47.584
is not part of the show.

00:04:47.584 --> 00:04:49.250
Because I think people
thought, oh, this

00:04:49.250 --> 00:04:51.770
is one of those exciting
moments where we've

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:53.645
gone into Beethoven's darkness.

00:04:53.645 --> 00:04:56.270
I've already explained that his
father beat the hell out of him

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:59.540
as a kid and that it's
possibly that's why

00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:02.610
he went deaf later in life,
because his father beat him.

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:06.320
We have clear evidence that his
father beat him as a child--

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:07.290
and his head.

00:05:07.290 --> 00:05:08.995
And so, I explain
to the audience,

00:05:08.995 --> 00:05:10.370
this has nothing
to do with that.

00:05:10.370 --> 00:05:12.020
Please, stay in your places.

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:13.490
Now, you don't
know you're dealing

00:05:13.490 --> 00:05:16.031
with a lot of different ages,
especially in a show like that.

00:05:16.031 --> 00:05:16.950
People begin to panic.

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:17.616
They got scared.

00:05:17.616 --> 00:05:19.370
I thought we did
OK, don't you think?

00:05:19.370 --> 00:05:22.190
But 600 people-- and I
thought, this is terrifying.

00:05:22.190 --> 00:05:23.370
It's black in this room.

00:05:23.370 --> 00:05:24.272
There's no way out.

00:05:24.272 --> 00:05:26.730
I said, ladies and gentlemen,
this is not part of the show.

00:05:26.730 --> 00:05:27.564
And it's not a joke.

00:05:27.564 --> 00:05:29.063
Something's happened
with the power.

00:05:29.063 --> 00:05:29.810
Just sit there.

00:05:29.810 --> 00:05:31.670
OK, so they sit.

00:05:31.670 --> 00:05:35.557
And then we wait for staff
to tell us what's going on,

00:05:35.557 --> 00:05:36.140
what happened.

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:38.870
What we find out later
is that some doofus

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:41.540
was playing with his
drone in the park

00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:45.410
and flew the drone into a
transformer and blew it up.

00:05:45.410 --> 00:05:49.100
So the entire of 1,600
people in Mountain View

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:51.140
didn't have electricity
for god-knows-what,

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:52.680
including our theater.

00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:55.250
Now, the lights only
come on for 20 minutes--

00:05:55.250 --> 00:05:57.470
the emergency lights.

00:05:57.470 --> 00:05:59.120
And so, I take off.

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:01.222
And I say, well,
figure it this way.

00:06:01.222 --> 00:06:02.930
Why don't I ask the
audience questions?--

00:06:02.930 --> 00:06:04.490
like I will with you today.

00:06:04.490 --> 00:06:06.000
And audience ask questions.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.540
So one lady says, I
saw all your shows.

00:06:08.540 --> 00:06:10.490
And I didn't see
the Gershwin show.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:12.860
So can you do me a
favor and tell us

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:14.030
about the Gershwin show?

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:15.720
And I said, why not?

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:17.930
And so, I played a little
bit of the Gershwin show--

00:06:17.930 --> 00:06:21.760
[MUSIC - GEORGE GERSHWIN,
 "RHAPSODY IN BLUE"]

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:27.770
--and explained that that theme
was sold to United Airlines

00:06:27.770 --> 00:06:31.970
for $3 million in
1980-- four bars--

00:06:31.970 --> 00:06:34.240
in 1985 or something like that.

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:36.290
So you can think of
George Gershwin, who

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:39.110
died at the age
of 38, not knowing

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:40.700
how successful he would become.

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:42.860
His brother, Ira--
and he died suddenly

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:45.020
from fulminating
brain tumor that he'd

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:46.190
had since he was a child.

00:06:46.190 --> 00:06:47.390
And it just fulminated.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:49.120
Imagine all that
music that we know.

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:51.320
Suddenly, at 38, [SNAPS]
just like that, America

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:52.670
lost such a voice.

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:56.910
And there, all of a sudden, we
have, all these years later,

00:06:56.910 --> 00:06:59.330
United Airlines buying
it for $3 million.

00:06:59.330 --> 00:07:00.830
I could suggest
that United Airlines

00:07:00.830 --> 00:07:03.440
would have spent better money
doing other things lately.

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:05.420
But you know, that's
a whole other story.

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:06.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:08.850
Maybe personal relations--
the kind of thing

00:07:08.850 --> 00:07:10.970
would probably be
better, ultimately,

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:14.210
to understand the value
of music and composing.

00:07:14.210 --> 00:07:18.820
And if we can only begin to
understand what Beethoven did--

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:21.860
the technology that is being
created here on these premises,

00:07:21.860 --> 00:07:24.800
things that are happening, is
essentially what Beethoven did,

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:27.200
a man who was completely
deaf, who changed

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:29.420
the entire world of music.

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:31.700
Up until Beethoven's
time, certainly,

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:33.950
when he started
to go deaf, music

00:07:33.950 --> 00:07:36.570
was essentially a
descriptive form.

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:37.490
There were rules.

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:40.300
What you never did was
fifths in parallels.

00:07:40.300 --> 00:07:41.572
[PIANO CHORDS]

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:47.330
You did a little bit
IN old church singing,

00:07:47.330 --> 00:07:48.080
but generally not.

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:49.390
Certainly, fourths never went.

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:50.234
[PIANO CHORDS]

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:52.800
Because that's kind of ugly.

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:54.960
There's something
wonderfully ugly about it.

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:57.270
And Beethoven started
breaking those rules.

00:07:57.270 --> 00:07:59.490
And of course, his
teacher, Haydn,

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:02.130
couldn't stand the fact
that Beethoven was actually

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:03.630
making ugly music.

00:08:03.630 --> 00:08:06.450
But while Beethoven was
busy making ugly music,

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:10.640
taking the first chord of the
"C Minor Pathetique Sonata"--

00:08:10.640 --> 00:08:11.510
[PIANO CHORD]

00:08:12.355 --> 00:08:12.980
Listen to that.

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:15.410
It doesn't sound like anything
except ugly, doesn't it?

00:08:15.410 --> 00:08:16.430
It's just thick.

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:16.970
It's ugly.

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:17.470
It's rich.

00:08:17.470 --> 00:08:18.734
[PIANO CHORDS]

00:08:19.630 --> 00:08:21.310
What does that mean?

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:25.050
Essentially, Beethoven broke
all the fine elegant rules

00:08:25.050 --> 00:08:26.120
of music-making.

00:08:26.120 --> 00:08:27.870
Whereas, Mozart would
have structured it--

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:28.920
[PIANO CHORDS]

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:32.159
--and somebody else-- Haydn
would have structured it,

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:35.549
Beethoven, he takes all the
emotion, all the energy,

00:08:35.549 --> 00:08:37.710
and he packs it
into a solid chord

00:08:37.710 --> 00:08:40.799
right at the very
beginning of a sonata,

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:43.500
right at the point where
he starts to go deaf.

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:44.790
Now, what does this do?

00:08:44.790 --> 00:08:46.200
This changes the world of music.

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:49.710
Because up until that
point, music was elegant.

00:08:49.710 --> 00:08:51.900
Suddenly, music became personal.

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:53.520
It became emotional.

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:57.540
It became an expression of a
man basically screaming inside,

00:08:57.540 --> 00:08:59.640
what is happening to me?

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:01.530
Now, you have to think--

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:02.520
look, I'm a musician--

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:04.230
God forbid it shouldn't happen--

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:05.970
I go deaf.

00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:08.324
It'll be painful for me
and a few of my friends

00:09:08.324 --> 00:09:09.240
that I will scream at.

00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:11.820
But quite, frankly
nobody will really care.

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:14.820
But Beethoven--
think of the person

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:17.010
who has changed
technology today,

00:09:17.010 --> 00:09:19.800
whoever that one
person is, suddenly

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:23.250
being impeded from being able
to do that, whatever it is.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.650
The brain stops
functioning, whatever it is.

00:09:25.650 --> 00:09:27.420
Or any one of you
who are developing

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:29.340
these incredible things today--

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:32.550
that suddenly, the one
gift that you have,

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:34.770
the one thing that you
have above everybody

00:09:34.770 --> 00:09:37.380
else-- in Beethoven's
case, perfect hearing

00:09:37.380 --> 00:09:41.730
and perfect sense of invention--
suddenly disappears on you.

00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:44.940
And you have enough
faculty left to understand

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:46.440
that that has disappeared.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:47.580
What do you do?

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:50.760
So here was a man
who was able to take

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:54.540
everything going against him and
still create beautiful music.

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:57.210
My theory has always been,
in the case of Beethoven,

00:09:57.210 --> 00:10:00.120
that music changed because
he couldn't self-edit.

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:03.380
Most of us, as we go through
life, we write things.

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:05.880
And then we say, ah, tomorrow,
I have to give a Google talk.

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:07.027
I'm going to write it down.

00:10:07.027 --> 00:10:08.610
And boy, I'm going
to sound brilliant.

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:10.590
Because, look, it's
just genius on paper.

00:10:10.590 --> 00:10:13.089
And then I stand up in front
of people, and I start talking.

00:10:13.089 --> 00:10:14.381
I sound like a total nitwit.

00:10:14.381 --> 00:10:14.880
Why?

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:18.240
Because what lives and
breathes in air and space

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:21.690
is very different than what
exists in your head on paper.

00:10:21.690 --> 00:10:24.350
In this kind of communication,
that has to work.

00:10:24.350 --> 00:10:26.400
So it takes a lifetime
to understand that.

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.830
Beethoven no longer
had the ability

00:10:28.830 --> 00:10:30.690
to go into a theater
in a concert hall,

00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:32.506
sit and listen,
and go, you know,

00:10:32.506 --> 00:10:33.630
that doesn't sound so good.

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:35.040
I think I meant that on paper.

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:37.390
But now, when I hear it
with the whole orchestra,

00:10:37.390 --> 00:10:38.820
it doesn't quite
work out for me.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:41.160
I think I should shift this
note here and this note there.

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:42.451
That'll give a different color.

00:10:42.451 --> 00:10:43.890
It will tell a different story.

00:10:43.890 --> 00:10:45.120
He didn't do that.

00:10:45.120 --> 00:10:47.550
What he did was,
essentially, put on paper

00:10:47.550 --> 00:10:51.720
what he imagined in the sonic
world that remained in his head

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:53.940
and left that for
us to interpret.

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:55.470
And because of
that, we were forced

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:59.580
to go to his sonic world in his
imagination, not a sonic world

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:05.310
that he fixed to make it correct
for us to hear and understand.

00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:06.960
Of course, when it
comes to Beethoven,

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:09.630
he still had a sense of
melody, a sense of harmony,

00:11:09.630 --> 00:11:11.090
that was absolutely beautiful.

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:13.340
One of the pieces that I'll
just play for you simply--

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:16.140
and then we can begin our
interactive discussion--

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:18.930
is the piece that, essentially,
was last published,

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:20.890
40 years after he died.

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:23.670
It was discovered-- and there
are several versions to it.

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:25.650
Nobody knows where
it really originated,

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:29.760
if the original notes that we
now play are his actual notes.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:33.000
But it's interesting that,
whatever it is, the story

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.680
that is behind all of it--

00:11:34.680 --> 00:11:37.350
discovering this
piece so much after he

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:40.560
died, not knowing to
who it was written,

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:42.250
because apparently--
several things.

00:11:42.250 --> 00:11:44.940
One, the inscription could
have been copied down wrong.

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:48.420
Or Beethoven's hand was so messy
that the guy who copied it down

00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:49.590
got the name wrong.

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:50.680
Nobody knows.

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:53.910
But this piece, "Fur Elise,"
that every student plays,

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:55.860
that every young person
plays when you get

00:11:55.860 --> 00:12:00.900
introduced to the piano, that
very piece is Beethoven Lore.

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:04.440
And yet, it's the lore that
we have put upon the piece.

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:07.200
And what is really interesting
about it is that it does

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:09.930
somehow reveal, in
its most basic form--

00:12:09.930 --> 00:12:12.230
probably composed in 1810--

00:12:12.230 --> 00:12:17.328
a very sensitive, very elegant,
and very heartfelt Beethoven.

00:12:17.328 --> 00:12:20.316
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "FUR ELISE"]

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:10.134
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:10.134 --> 00:15:14.475
Simple and elegant
and beautiful-- so now

00:15:14.475 --> 00:15:16.100
the floor gets to be
open to questions.

00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:18.170
And you get to ask
anything about Beethoven,

00:15:18.170 --> 00:15:20.540
about what it is I do,
anything you want to know.

00:15:20.540 --> 00:15:22.880
But you must ask, in order
to make this fun and work.

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:24.450
So go ahead.

00:15:24.450 --> 00:15:25.100
Don't be shy.

00:15:25.100 --> 00:15:26.240
Over there, I saw
you have a question.

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:27.500
SPEAKER 1: But wait
for the microphone.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:28.730
HERSHEY FELDER: Now, wait
for the microphone, they say.

00:15:28.730 --> 00:15:29.090
Anybody?

00:15:29.090 --> 00:15:29.630
Yes, over there.

00:15:29.630 --> 00:15:31.338
There's a gentlemen
at the-- no, not you.

00:15:31.338 --> 00:15:32.450
Right here, the lady.

00:15:32.450 --> 00:15:34.130
Go ahead.

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:35.750
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:15:35.750 --> 00:15:38.184
We saw your show last night
and absolutely loved it.

00:15:38.184 --> 00:15:40.100
HERSHEY FELDER: Say that
louder, a lot louder.

00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:41.869
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:41.869 --> 00:15:44.077
AUDIENCE: We saw the show
last night in Mountain View

00:15:44.077 --> 00:15:45.300
and absolutely loved it.

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:46.758
HERSHEY FELDER:
Now it's well done.

00:15:46.758 --> 00:15:47.484
Yes!

00:15:47.484 --> 00:15:48.650
Thank you, that's very kind.

00:15:48.650 --> 00:15:49.880
Thank you for coming.

00:15:49.880 --> 00:15:52.810
AUDIENCE: In the
program notes, where

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:55.820
it says, more biographical
information about some

00:15:55.820 --> 00:15:58.370
of the other people who were
involved in the production,

00:15:58.370 --> 00:16:00.870
it doesn't say, for instance,
where you were born,

00:16:00.870 --> 00:16:02.519
where you were educated--

00:16:02.519 --> 00:16:03.310
HERSHEY FELDER: OK.

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:04.130
AUDIENCE: Things like that.

00:16:04.130 --> 00:16:05.420
HERSHEY FELDER: Things
like that-- so basic things

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:07.310
about me, where I was
born, I was educated.

00:16:07.310 --> 00:16:11.660
I was born in a land far
off, very much so north.

00:16:11.660 --> 00:16:13.710
I am an immigrant
to this country.

00:16:13.710 --> 00:16:16.580
I was born, essentially,
where we all live in igloos

00:16:16.580 --> 00:16:19.880
and cook outside and
hunt fish and whatever.

00:16:19.880 --> 00:16:25.120
I was born in Montreal, Canada
and came to this country

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:27.290
30 years ago to study.

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:29.360
And I went to study
with Jerry Lowenthal,

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:31.690
a great pianist at Juilliard.

00:16:31.690 --> 00:16:32.690
And he was the director.

00:16:32.690 --> 00:16:34.065
I was not a student
at Juilliard.

00:16:34.065 --> 00:16:36.080
But I was one of his
private students.

00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:37.530
I was an apprentice,
I would say.

00:16:37.530 --> 00:16:39.170
And I was beginning
to develop my life

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:40.700
in New York and
this understanding

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:42.830
that I wanted to do
both theater and music.

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:47.060
I had a proper training,
as a kid in Montreal--

00:16:47.060 --> 00:16:49.280
great musicians there, fabulous.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:51.050
And then I went,
as a young person,

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:52.760
to McGill, when I was 13.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:55.120
And I studied piano
there with Dorothy Morton

00:16:55.120 --> 00:16:56.090
and Eugene Plawutsky.

00:16:56.090 --> 00:16:57.260
And I studied composition.

00:16:57.260 --> 00:17:00.410
And I studied
conducting and really

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:03.140
set on a path of wanting to
do something that nobody did,

00:17:03.140 --> 00:17:05.810
which was combining theater
and music all into one.

00:17:05.810 --> 00:17:07.940
And as I said earlier,
everybody laughed at that,

00:17:07.940 --> 00:17:10.099
because it's not something
that goes together.

00:17:10.099 --> 00:17:11.520
It doesn't make sense.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:13.444
First of all, acting
is very extroverted.

00:17:13.444 --> 00:17:15.319
And I was an actor as
a young person as well.

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:18.380
I studied traditional acting
in proper theater school.

00:17:18.380 --> 00:17:19.700
And I grew up as an actor.

00:17:19.700 --> 00:17:22.160
But I also grew up as a
pianist and a musician.

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:24.530
And I was told very
often-- in fact,

00:17:24.530 --> 00:17:26.839
when I auditioned for Yale
as a kid, as a 15-year-old--

00:17:26.839 --> 00:17:28.790
which was a nutso thing to do--

00:17:28.790 --> 00:17:30.680
for the acting
program, they were

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:32.990
talking about my
accomplishments as a pianist.

00:17:32.990 --> 00:17:35.360
And they said, well, you
need to pay attention

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:36.840
to one or the other.

00:17:36.840 --> 00:17:39.170
And it became very clear to
me, for the next 10 years,

00:17:39.170 --> 00:17:41.150
I needed to spend
time with music.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:44.300
Because one can always learn
to become a better actor as one

00:17:44.300 --> 00:17:45.080
grows.

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:47.580
But if you don't pay attention
to your music as you grow up,

00:17:47.580 --> 00:17:48.480
you're finished.

00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:50.840
So for the next 10 years,
although I acted a little bit,

00:17:50.840 --> 00:17:53.930
I paid very close attention
to both musicianship

00:17:53.930 --> 00:17:56.540
and studying the
real craft of music.

00:17:56.540 --> 00:18:00.590
Then, when I was
26, 27-years-old,

00:18:00.590 --> 00:18:03.650
this whole notion of creating
"Gershwin" came together.

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:05.210
I opened it in Los Angeles.

00:18:05.210 --> 00:18:06.651
And stars started showing up.

00:18:06.651 --> 00:18:08.150
And I thought,
what's going on here?

00:18:08.150 --> 00:18:09.470
Something's very wrong.

00:18:09.470 --> 00:18:11.870
The kinds of characters
that showed up to see me--

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:14.120
popular stars, Warren
Beatty and Annette Bening

00:18:14.120 --> 00:18:17.280
and Neil Simon and
Paul Thomas Anderson,

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:18.440
movie-makers and so on.

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:20.490
I said, I may be
on to something.

00:18:20.490 --> 00:18:22.370
And it took off and,
within a few years,

00:18:22.370 --> 00:18:25.745
became the Gershwins' highest
growing entity for the estate.

00:18:25.745 --> 00:18:27.620
And I thought, maybe
there's a story to this.

00:18:27.620 --> 00:18:28.850
Why don't I do Chopin?

00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:30.020
Everybody laughed.

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:30.980
Nobody's going to come.

00:18:30.980 --> 00:18:31.850
I did that.

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:33.470
And it worked.

00:18:33.470 --> 00:18:38.840
And I took us into Poland and
Paris in the 1830s and 1840s.

00:18:38.840 --> 00:18:40.310
And everybody laughed at me.

00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:40.820
Fine.

00:18:40.820 --> 00:18:42.000
Then, that worked.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:43.310
And then, I said, I'm
going to do Beethoven.

00:18:43.310 --> 00:18:44.610
And everybody laughed at that.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:46.190
They said, nobody will come.

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:47.270
Nobody cares.

00:18:47.270 --> 00:18:48.650
Nobody's interested.

00:18:48.650 --> 00:18:52.280
Yesterday, it was announced
that it broke the record here

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:54.770
by, I think, 300% or 400%.

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:56.970
So it's not about
me or what I do.

00:18:56.970 --> 00:18:58.980
I'm just a vehicle to
tell these stories.

00:18:58.980 --> 00:19:01.850
It's about these characters
and how much they mean.

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:04.660
And as technology advances,
as we learn new things,

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:06.410
one of the interesting
things is to always

00:19:06.410 --> 00:19:09.560
look at people who came
before us who changed whatever

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:12.650
technical means and
whatever things that changed

00:19:12.650 --> 00:19:16.117
the world, as we grew
up, as they grew up,

00:19:16.117 --> 00:19:17.450
and to understand what they did.

00:19:17.450 --> 00:19:20.090
And for me, the most interesting
thing about Beethoven

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:21.830
or Gershwin or anyone--

00:19:21.830 --> 00:19:23.060
you think about Gershwin.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:24.110
And we now know jazz.

00:19:24.110 --> 00:19:26.510
But you think about
that clarinet solo

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:28.100
at the beginning
of "The Rhapsody."

00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:30.525
It starts with a
trill like this.

00:19:30.525 --> 00:19:31.475
[PIANO CHORDS]

00:19:31.475 --> 00:19:35.385
And then, the clarinet is placed
half way, up till about there.

00:19:35.385 --> 00:19:36.510
And then he bends the note.

00:19:36.510 --> 00:19:39.417
"Oo-wya-a da-da-da-da."

00:19:39.417 --> 00:19:40.750
On the piano, you can't do that.

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:42.208
Because a piano
doesn't bend notes.

00:19:42.208 --> 00:19:43.330
They're specific, right?

00:19:43.330 --> 00:19:44.470
So you do this.

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:49.460
[MUSIC - GEORGE GERSHWIN,
 "RHAPSODY IN BLUE"]

00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:50.540
We hear that today.

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:52.430
It sounds like we're going
to take off in an airplane

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:53.554
and everything's going to--

00:19:53.554 --> 00:19:54.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:54.740 --> 00:19:56.870
Or you're going to be
told, in various languages,

00:19:56.870 --> 00:19:58.390
to put your suit on like this.

00:19:58.390 --> 00:19:59.960
And if you go in
water, this thing

00:19:59.960 --> 00:20:01.251
goes-- blowing in your whistle.

00:20:01.251 --> 00:20:03.425
Whatever.

00:20:03.425 --> 00:20:06.080
The point is to be
ridiculous and funny as well.

00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:09.890
But when something
like that happens,

00:20:09.890 --> 00:20:11.970
the interesting
thing for all of us,

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:16.190
whatever it is we do invent,
is to think back before that.

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:20.240
Think back to something that
seems evident and obvious

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:25.160
to us today and a given and what
must have been like to invent

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:28.410
something like that.

00:20:28.410 --> 00:20:31.460
Interestingly enough, Gershwin
did write a glissando.

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:34.250
Now, a glissando, essentially,
if you're on the piano,

00:20:34.250 --> 00:20:34.790
means this.

00:20:34.790 --> 00:20:36.420
[PIANO SCALE]

00:20:36.420 --> 00:20:39.206
You take the back of your
finger and you roll up the keys.

00:20:39.206 --> 00:20:41.080
And it sort of connects
the keys in that way.

00:20:41.080 --> 00:20:42.140
It's not an even scale.

00:20:42.140 --> 00:20:44.120
It just "schwoo"-- like that.

00:20:44.120 --> 00:20:46.970
But if you write a
glissando in a clarinet,

00:20:46.970 --> 00:20:48.530
it's a different kind of thing.

00:20:48.530 --> 00:20:49.880
He did write that.

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:51.560
But the story goes
that they were

00:20:51.560 --> 00:20:53.600
busy rehearsing "The
Rhapsody in Blue"

00:20:53.600 --> 00:20:59.750
in 1924 for the first appearance
in 43rd Street at Aeolian Hall.

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:02.150
And apparently, the
clarinetist was bored.

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:03.080
He was bored to tears.

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:04.430
The rehearsal was boring.

00:21:04.430 --> 00:21:05.840
And he was just
fidgeting around.

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:11.700
And he went la-da-da-da-da
da-da-da-da-raaah nya-na-na.

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:14.190
And then suddenly, you
heard this screaming siren.

00:21:14.190 --> 00:21:15.750
And everybody thought
George Gershwin

00:21:15.750 --> 00:21:17.940
was going to fly off the
handle and get really mad.

00:21:17.940 --> 00:21:19.410
But George Gershwin,
the inventor,

00:21:19.410 --> 00:21:22.120
realized, this is
going to change music.

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:25.740
And he kept that crazy
clarinet glissando in,

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:28.280
that screaming siren
that basically announced,

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:29.300
jazz is here.

00:21:29.300 --> 00:21:30.630
Jazz is here to stay.

00:21:30.630 --> 00:21:32.370
Jazz is in the concert hall.

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:33.720
And it's important.

00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:34.570
Fine.

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:37.080
But think back to the
day before that rehearsal

00:21:37.080 --> 00:21:39.480
when that sound didn't
exist, a sound that we

00:21:39.480 --> 00:21:41.730
consider so American now.

00:21:41.730 --> 00:21:44.010
Or a dance rhythm that you--

00:21:44.010 --> 00:21:44.790
[SINGING]

00:21:44.790 --> 00:21:49.530
[UPBEAT MUSIC]

00:21:49.530 --> 00:21:51.170
That kind of stuff,
before it existed,

00:21:51.170 --> 00:21:52.770
where did this stuff come from?

00:21:52.770 --> 00:21:56.100
Similarly, to
Beethoven-- the story

00:21:56.100 --> 00:21:58.170
goes that "The Fifth
Symphony," that it's

00:21:58.170 --> 00:21:59.670
fate knocking on the door.

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:00.690
And he heard his fate.

00:22:00.690 --> 00:22:01.830
And he was going deaf.

00:22:01.830 --> 00:22:03.670
And everything was going wrong.

00:22:03.670 --> 00:22:04.320
Ta-ta-ta-ta!

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:05.820
God is coming to get me.

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:07.470
And Beethoven said,
absolutely not.

00:22:07.470 --> 00:22:08.970
I went for a walk in the park.

00:22:08.970 --> 00:22:11.140
I felt a little bird
knocking on a tree.

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:12.996
[KNOCKING]

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:15.380
And all of a sudden--

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:17.320
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "FIFTH

00:22:17.320 --> 00:22:19.745
SYMPHONY"]

00:22:19.745 --> 00:22:21.430
A little bird knocking.

00:22:21.430 --> 00:22:23.254
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "FIFTH

00:22:23.254 --> 00:22:25.990
SYMPHONY"]

00:22:25.990 --> 00:22:27.100
It's actually very sweet.

00:22:27.100 --> 00:22:27.850
It doesn't start--

00:22:27.850 --> 00:22:28.690
[ROUGH PLAYING]

00:22:28.690 --> 00:22:30.730
No, it's pianissimo--
piano, actually.

00:22:30.730 --> 00:22:32.815
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "FIFTH
 SYMPHONY"]

00:22:32.815 --> 00:22:33.565
And it's mystical.

00:22:33.565 --> 00:22:44.014
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "FIFTH
 SYMPHONY"]

00:22:44.014 --> 00:22:46.360
The invention of the composer--

00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:49.620
what you hear in
something very simple,

00:22:49.620 --> 00:22:52.780
in the most basic element
that suddenly blossoms

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:55.131
into a whole other world.

00:22:55.131 --> 00:22:56.380
And that's what Beethoven did.

00:22:56.380 --> 00:23:00.340
And the deafer he got, the more
inventive the music became.

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:03.850
He went into this sonic universe
that was in his imagination.

00:23:03.850 --> 00:23:06.280
And it was actually miraculous.

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:09.040
And why it's so interesting
to talk about this stuff here

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:11.410
is because, 100
and some odd years

00:23:11.410 --> 00:23:14.470
ago, had he had
this opportunity,

00:23:14.470 --> 00:23:17.080
he would be the one talking
about the kinds of things

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:18.410
that you are doing.

00:23:18.410 --> 00:23:20.230
And that's what I
find fascinating,

00:23:20.230 --> 00:23:23.260
to think about the day
before the inventor appeared

00:23:23.260 --> 00:23:26.630
on the scene, the day before
the invention appeared there.

00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:28.690
What does it take
to get to something

00:23:28.690 --> 00:23:32.140
that has no reference to
what has come before it?

00:23:32.140 --> 00:23:34.720
Or draws on what has
come before it only

00:23:34.720 --> 00:23:36.730
to invent something new?

00:23:36.730 --> 00:23:39.340
I have been a
specialist in looking

00:23:39.340 --> 00:23:42.820
at the day of the invention
and what has been done.

00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:45.010
To try and invent
something new, to me,

00:23:45.010 --> 00:23:47.140
is beyond even the imagination.

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:48.850
Where does that
miracle come from?

00:23:48.850 --> 00:23:50.020
And how does it happen?

00:23:50.020 --> 00:23:52.600
And that's a fascinating
thing to think about.

00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:53.846
Another question, please.

00:23:53.846 --> 00:23:54.470
Yes, over here.

00:23:57.079 --> 00:23:59.370
AUDIENCE: This is a question
I've been pondering about.

00:23:59.370 --> 00:24:00.740
I think it's related.

00:24:00.740 --> 00:24:03.900
When does a collection
of noises become music?

00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:04.400
There's a--

00:24:04.400 --> 00:24:06.400
HERSHEY FELDER: When does
a collection of noises

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:06.950
become music?

00:24:06.950 --> 00:24:09.200
Well, for certain
composers, as soon

00:24:09.200 --> 00:24:11.780
as they get up in the morning
and go to the bathroom,

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:14.840
that noise is apparently music.

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:18.860
And so the question is less,
when does it become music?

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:22.880
When did a white painting
become great art?

00:24:22.880 --> 00:24:24.080
At what point?

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:26.940
So who defines what that is?

00:24:26.940 --> 00:24:29.570
Well, for me, the best
story of that is Chopin.

00:24:29.570 --> 00:24:31.160
Everybody has inventions.

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:33.020
And there's a
funny Jewish story.

00:24:33.020 --> 00:24:33.950
I love this story.

00:24:33.950 --> 00:24:36.030
And it's all about storytelling.

00:24:36.030 --> 00:24:40.370
So it's a modern art exhibition.

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:41.990
It happens in LA.

00:24:41.990 --> 00:24:44.480
And I'll explain
later what it means.

00:24:44.480 --> 00:24:46.640
A modern art exhibition
that happens in LA.

00:24:46.640 --> 00:24:47.510
And people go.

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:48.860
And there's this white canvas.

00:24:48.860 --> 00:24:49.760
It's huge.

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:51.140
It's 5' by 3'.

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:52.806
It's sitting there
in the museum.

00:24:52.806 --> 00:24:53.930
And the critics are coming.

00:24:53.930 --> 00:24:54.817
Ooh!

00:24:54.817 --> 00:24:55.316
Ah!

00:24:55.316 --> 00:24:57.070
[GASP] Look what's inside!

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:57.740
Ooh!

00:24:57.740 --> 00:24:58.250
It's white.

00:24:58.250 --> 00:24:58.749
It's blank.

00:24:58.749 --> 00:24:59.500
Ooh!

00:24:59.500 --> 00:25:00.290
Ahh!

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:02.930
Don't you see what that is?

00:25:02.930 --> 00:25:04.670
Three weeks later,
the same artist

00:25:04.670 --> 00:25:07.730
comes back with a development
on the first thing.

00:25:07.730 --> 00:25:09.860
He comes with the
same white painting

00:25:09.860 --> 00:25:14.810
except, in the lower right hand
corner, are two small dots.

00:25:14.810 --> 00:25:16.670
The critics come and they look.

00:25:16.670 --> 00:25:17.780
And they analyze.

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:19.850
And they look at the two
small dots and go, egh!

00:25:19.850 --> 00:25:23.840
[YIDDISH]

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:27.530
So [YIDDISH] means, eh,
overstuffed, too much, too--

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:28.610
that's the whole thing.

00:25:28.610 --> 00:25:29.210
What is art?

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:32.660
Art is in the perception of the
person who is looking at it.

00:25:32.660 --> 00:25:36.380
But for me, Chopin
really got it right.

00:25:36.380 --> 00:25:39.440
Art really is created
by the artist.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:42.470
But time is the deciding factor.

00:25:42.470 --> 00:25:43.550
He said this.

00:25:43.550 --> 00:25:45.840
He said, I have no idea
if this piece is good.

00:25:45.840 --> 00:25:47.460
In 100 years, ask me.

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:48.960
And I will tell you.

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:50.930
And that's really the idea.

00:25:50.930 --> 00:25:52.310
An artist can have an idea.

00:25:52.310 --> 00:25:54.410
But what we think
today is great art--

00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:55.850
and this is what's interesting.

00:25:55.850 --> 00:25:58.430
What is purported as
being by the critics,

00:25:58.430 --> 00:26:00.530
be it a play or this or that--

00:26:00.530 --> 00:26:03.020
people are talking about the
new play "Hamilton" and so on.

00:26:03.020 --> 00:26:04.186
It's a very effective piece.

00:26:04.186 --> 00:26:06.380
I've seen it on Broadway twice.

00:26:06.380 --> 00:26:07.880
Will it be around in 100 years?

00:26:07.880 --> 00:26:10.460
And will it mean the
same thing in 100 years

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:13.280
that even "Fiddler on the
Roof" now means to us,

00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:16.489
even though it was created
those 60 years ago?

00:26:16.489 --> 00:26:17.030
50 years ago?

00:26:17.030 --> 00:26:17.890
Or whatever it is?

00:26:17.890 --> 00:26:19.880
--a little bit more than that.

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:20.660
We don't know.

00:26:20.660 --> 00:26:23.070
We can only know then.

00:26:23.070 --> 00:26:25.310
And time is the great
decider for that.

00:26:25.310 --> 00:26:27.110
So when does art become art?

00:26:27.110 --> 00:26:28.670
When does noise become art?

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:31.310
George Gershwin said
that he would go down

00:26:31.310 --> 00:26:34.370
the streets of Manhattan
and the noise of the city

00:26:34.370 --> 00:26:36.140
is what created his music.

00:26:36.140 --> 00:26:38.210
Beethoven-- it was
obviously the noise

00:26:38.210 --> 00:26:43.130
that was in his spirit that
had to come out in that way.

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:46.400
What I think art becomes is
when it touches enough people

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:47.660
to mean something.

00:26:47.660 --> 00:26:50.600
That's when noise becomes music.

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:54.110
It's not defined by
the artist as a rule.

00:26:54.110 --> 00:26:56.510
And it's not defined by
an audience as a rule.

00:26:56.510 --> 00:26:59.870
It's defined as how
long it takes for art

00:26:59.870 --> 00:27:03.590
to become something that goes
into the spirit and moves

00:27:03.590 --> 00:27:04.190
people.

00:27:04.190 --> 00:27:05.780
And if it moves people,
it will stick around.

00:27:05.780 --> 00:27:07.690
That's why Shakespeare
is still around.

00:27:07.690 --> 00:27:10.040
This stuff is still
around because it's human.

00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:11.510
And I think the
artists who stick

00:27:11.510 --> 00:27:14.900
to being human and not
pretentious or cleverer

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:18.470
than are the artists who tend
to stick around the longest.

00:27:18.470 --> 00:27:21.890
And the struggle is to find
the honesty in the work,

00:27:21.890 --> 00:27:23.770
to make sure that that happens.

00:27:23.770 --> 00:27:26.390
And in far as my own work,
that's a struggle every day,

00:27:26.390 --> 00:27:28.430
is not to be pretentious
about what it is,

00:27:28.430 --> 00:27:31.850
to just be simple and
straightforward and human.

00:27:31.850 --> 00:27:34.130
And I think the danger
now is, because there

00:27:34.130 --> 00:27:36.630
is so much pretense
on the internet

00:27:36.630 --> 00:27:40.010
and so everybody has an opinion,
is that people try to please

00:27:40.010 --> 00:27:41.954
too many people too often.

00:27:41.954 --> 00:27:44.120
And so what lands up happening
is a lot of pretense,

00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:46.610
as opposed to just a
simple honest expression,

00:27:46.610 --> 00:27:48.859
and let it out there
to see what happens.

00:27:48.859 --> 00:27:49.900
Another question, please.

00:27:49.900 --> 00:27:53.439
Yes, over there-- gentleman

00:27:53.439 --> 00:27:55.480
AUDIENCE: I have a related
question to that also.

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:55.840
HERSHEY FELDER: Sure.

00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:57.890
AUDIENCE: So, in tech, it's
actually quite easy for us

00:27:57.890 --> 00:27:58.390
to invent.

00:27:58.390 --> 00:28:00.731
Because we just look for
challenges people have.

00:28:00.731 --> 00:28:02.230
And then we just
find the challenge,

00:28:02.230 --> 00:28:04.810
and the invention kind
of happens naturally.

00:28:04.810 --> 00:28:08.170
And I've heard from some people
that these great artists often

00:28:08.170 --> 00:28:09.820
used the world as a mirror.

00:28:09.820 --> 00:28:11.590
And they're making
music that mirrors,

00:28:11.590 --> 00:28:15.610
like, a social movement, some
outlet for people to have

00:28:15.610 --> 00:28:17.360
an outlet for their emotions.

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:19.676
And I wanted to see if
there's truth to that

00:28:19.676 --> 00:28:20.800
and what your thoughts are.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:21.605
Maybe there are other ways.

00:28:21.605 --> 00:28:21.870
HERSHEY FELDER: Sure.

00:28:21.870 --> 00:28:22.930
AUDIENCE: How do
people get [INAUDIBLE]..

00:28:22.930 --> 00:28:25.471
HERSHEY FELDER: Well, what you
are saying, in terms of people

00:28:25.471 --> 00:28:28.690
are looking, in your business,
for a need for something

00:28:28.690 --> 00:28:29.350
specific.

00:28:29.350 --> 00:28:31.690
And then the inventor
goes and follows the need.

00:28:31.690 --> 00:28:33.800
I think, similarly
to the artist,

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:35.830
people are looking
for human connection.

00:28:35.830 --> 00:28:38.890
They're looking for anything
that will be, like you say,

00:28:38.890 --> 00:28:41.110
the mirror, or will
relate to their own lives,

00:28:41.110 --> 00:28:43.900
or will be able to be
a form of expression.

00:28:43.900 --> 00:28:47.200
And I think the artist
is intending very much

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:48.940
to say that.

00:28:48.940 --> 00:28:51.310
And I've always said about
the performance art, when

00:28:51.310 --> 00:28:55.510
it comes to performance
art, if someone is just

00:28:55.510 --> 00:28:57.310
wanting to perform
for themselves

00:28:57.310 --> 00:29:00.630
and not taking the audience into
any kind of consideration, what

00:29:00.630 --> 00:29:04.210
lands up happening is perform in
your basement for your mirror.

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:05.830
You perform for yourself.

00:29:05.830 --> 00:29:08.530
But the whole thing is
interrelated and very much so

00:29:08.530 --> 00:29:10.210
exactly what you say.

00:29:10.210 --> 00:29:11.550
You find the need.

00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:12.440
You find the niche.

00:29:12.440 --> 00:29:14.470
And you go in there,
and you tell the story

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:16.090
or create the invention.

00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:19.810
Similarly, for artists,
I think artists find

00:29:19.810 --> 00:29:21.610
a story that needs to be told.

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:22.660
They tell it.

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:24.820
And somehow, there is
an audience for it.

00:29:24.820 --> 00:29:25.829
There's two types.

00:29:25.829 --> 00:29:27.370
There's a lot of
fashion in Hollywood

00:29:27.370 --> 00:29:31.480
today to create art
for the audience that's

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:33.610
going to buy, for the
tweeners or whatever,

00:29:33.610 --> 00:29:35.390
so on and so forth.

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:38.030
And the idea of the artist
is to take that need

00:29:38.030 --> 00:29:39.419
and to push even beyond.

00:29:39.419 --> 00:29:41.710
Then, there are artists who
don't care what anybody has

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:43.162
to say about anything they do.

00:29:43.162 --> 00:29:44.120
And they just go ahead.

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:47.560
So art-- it can be
very many things.

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:50.320
But one thing that's very
important is commercial art

00:29:50.320 --> 00:29:52.810
or art that is
being sold, art that

00:29:52.810 --> 00:29:57.340
actually is valuable
dollar-wise, is not dirty.

00:29:57.340 --> 00:30:00.130
And that has been a very
big mistake over the years.

00:30:00.130 --> 00:30:01.560
Some of the greatest art--

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:04.300
the Beethovens, the
Chopins, the Gershwins--

00:30:04.300 --> 00:30:07.150
they were all highly
conscious that their art had

00:30:07.150 --> 00:30:09.430
to be sold, that they
need to make a living.

00:30:09.430 --> 00:30:12.400
And there is monetary
value to their art.

00:30:12.400 --> 00:30:14.400
And this notion of
living like a poor artist

00:30:14.400 --> 00:30:18.610
in some dreg in some basement
in Manhattan with roaches--

00:30:18.610 --> 00:30:20.440
that's absolute nonsense.

00:30:20.440 --> 00:30:24.100
An artist is a person who sees
the world in a certain way

00:30:24.100 --> 00:30:26.020
and then reflects it
through their medium,

00:30:26.020 --> 00:30:30.170
through their prism, to
other people to share.

00:30:30.170 --> 00:30:32.180
So it's exactly what
you're saying it is.

00:30:32.180 --> 00:30:34.420
It is that mirror,
that reflection.

00:30:34.420 --> 00:30:35.566
Someone else.

00:30:35.566 --> 00:30:36.940
We'll go back over
there perhaps.

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:38.128
SPEAKER 1: [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:42.720
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:46.290
I'm curious about the design
elements of your performances.

00:30:46.290 --> 00:30:48.300
Because, for example,
the Beethoven show

00:30:48.300 --> 00:30:50.490
is set in a cemetery--

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:51.522
kind of dark.

00:30:51.522 --> 00:30:52.230
Whereas, Chopin--

00:30:52.230 --> 00:30:52.800
HERSHEY FELDER: Fun!

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:53.940
Its fun in a cemetery.

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:54.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:54.660 --> 00:30:55.861
No, I'm kidding.

00:30:55.861 --> 00:30:57.360
AUDIENCE: It was
interesting though.

00:30:57.360 --> 00:30:59.850
When you're portraying
Beethoven as--

00:30:59.850 --> 00:31:02.070
well, reflecting
back in his youth,

00:31:02.070 --> 00:31:04.277
it's kind of an
odd juxtaposition.

00:31:04.277 --> 00:31:06.360
Because it's looking forward
to his ultimate death

00:31:06.360 --> 00:31:08.010
and the final scene and so on.

00:31:08.010 --> 00:31:10.320
But then, "Chopin"-- you
had it set in a salon.

00:31:10.320 --> 00:31:12.641
And there's the whole framing
of the lesson and so on.

00:31:12.641 --> 00:31:15.015
So I'm curious about how you
make those design decisions.

00:31:15.015 --> 00:31:16.010
HERSHEY FELDER: Mm-hm, sure.

00:31:16.010 --> 00:31:18.290
AUDIENCE: To trade off the
art versus the performance

00:31:18.290 --> 00:31:18.915
versus the set.

00:31:18.915 --> 00:31:19.789
HERSHEY FELDER: Sure.

00:31:19.789 --> 00:31:22.080
Well, one of the things
that has been very integral

00:31:22.080 --> 00:31:26.130
in the creation of these pieces
is to set them in a location

00:31:26.130 --> 00:31:28.020
whereby the audience
makes sense.

00:31:28.020 --> 00:31:32.280
For instance, today we're
having a discussion in a set up

00:31:32.280 --> 00:31:37.290
whereby I'm a talker-speaker
and you are visitors,

00:31:37.290 --> 00:31:38.070
hearing me speak.

00:31:38.070 --> 00:31:40.239
Similarly, you're
here for a reason.

00:31:40.239 --> 00:31:41.280
You're here to hear this.

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:42.810
People come to the theater.

00:31:42.810 --> 00:31:44.292
They have to be
there for a reason.

00:31:44.292 --> 00:31:46.500
If you're going to give a
conceit to a one-man piece,

00:31:46.500 --> 00:31:48.420
where I'm going to
talk to you directly,

00:31:48.420 --> 00:31:50.430
there has to be a reason
for you to be there.

00:31:50.430 --> 00:31:53.040
There has to be a reason
for me to do the talking.

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:56.130
Otherwise, we are struggling
for the hour and a half

00:31:56.130 --> 00:31:58.500
to figure out why
any of us are there.

00:31:58.500 --> 00:32:00.180
So I begin with a concept.

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:01.540
You talk about "Chopin."

00:32:01.540 --> 00:32:03.540
"Chopin"-- it wasn't
that it was a salon

00:32:03.540 --> 00:32:05.970
and that it was
just there because.

00:32:05.970 --> 00:32:07.560
The interesting
thing about Chopin

00:32:07.560 --> 00:32:12.150
was that he had seen this
woman that he was ostensibly

00:32:12.150 --> 00:32:17.410
in love with after a year of
her having thrown him out.

00:32:17.410 --> 00:32:19.530
And they ran into
each other by accident

00:32:19.530 --> 00:32:22.110
on a staircase in Paris.

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:24.775
As she was leaving a
friend, he was going up

00:32:24.775 --> 00:32:26.400
to the friend, or
the other way around.

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:27.839
He was leaving the
friend for tea.

00:32:27.839 --> 00:32:29.130
And she was going into the tea.

00:32:29.130 --> 00:32:32.040
And they had broken up in a
terrible breakup a year before.

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:32.890
They see each other.

00:32:32.890 --> 00:32:35.490
They barely have what
to say to one another.

00:32:35.490 --> 00:32:39.330
And he then is heading
to teach a piano class.

00:32:39.330 --> 00:32:44.220
So I wondered, what would
happen if I, as Chopin, had

00:32:44.220 --> 00:32:47.190
run into this woman who'd
caused me such great pain a year

00:32:47.190 --> 00:32:50.190
before and then had to
go teach those students?

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:52.950
I can assume that the students
would pay dearly for what

00:32:52.950 --> 00:32:54.930
just happened just before.

00:32:54.930 --> 00:32:56.340
And so, that's the setup.

00:32:56.340 --> 00:32:58.170
So all the setups
for all these plays

00:32:58.170 --> 00:33:03.600
come from a very conscious
conceit of where we are,

00:33:03.600 --> 00:33:06.154
why I'm talking, and
why you are listening.

00:33:06.154 --> 00:33:08.070
In the case of "Beethoven,"
the reason it's in

00:33:08.070 --> 00:33:10.486
a cemetery is because the story
actually took place there.

00:33:10.486 --> 00:33:11.220
It's true.

00:33:11.220 --> 00:33:12.930
It's not a false conceit.

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:17.280
They actually disinterred
Beethoven's bones in 1863,

00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:20.820
because someone on the Music
Society Committee in Vienna

00:33:20.820 --> 00:33:24.420
had this idea that they needed
to put his remains in a metal

00:33:24.420 --> 00:33:27.480
coffin and to spare
them from further decay.

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:30.720
It was everybody's fascination
in the 1860s with bones

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:33.420
and phrenology and
trying to understand

00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:35.010
where people come from.

00:33:35.010 --> 00:33:36.930
And they would feel
the scalps of people

00:33:36.930 --> 00:33:38.049
and so on and so forth.

00:33:38.049 --> 00:33:39.590
So this was a very
interesting thing.

00:33:39.590 --> 00:33:40.950
I found that fascinating.

00:33:40.950 --> 00:33:42.240
That's where it takes place.

00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:43.781
And the people who
are gathered there

00:33:43.781 --> 00:33:47.190
are the people who actually
gathered at this disinterment.

00:33:47.190 --> 00:33:48.720
All of a sudden,
the bones come out.

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:51.660
And the person who was
presiding over the disinterment

00:33:51.660 --> 00:33:54.852
is saying, we need to keep
these bones up above the earth,

00:33:54.852 --> 00:33:56.310
because the future
of medicine will

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:58.590
be able to determine
what exactly happened

00:33:58.590 --> 00:34:00.850
to Beethoven, why he went deaf.

00:34:00.850 --> 00:34:03.930
And he wanted to know this.

00:34:03.930 --> 00:34:05.400
Let's keep the bones above.

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:07.590
And the committee
makes the argument, no.

00:34:07.590 --> 00:34:10.320
We need to keep
them in the earth.

00:34:10.320 --> 00:34:13.790
We need to put them back,
according to tradition.

00:34:13.790 --> 00:34:16.800
And of course, the doctor,
this Gerhard Von Breuning,

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:19.679
the narrator in this story,
steals two of the bones

00:34:19.679 --> 00:34:22.080
before anybody
knows and can tell.

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:24.150
And those bones,
interestingly enough,

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:26.940
seem to have been at
the Beethoven Center

00:34:26.940 --> 00:34:33.040
here at SJSU for many years,
until DNA testing demonstrated

00:34:33.040 --> 00:34:34.449
for us they were a fraud.

00:34:34.449 --> 00:34:36.120
Now, the interesting
thing about that--

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:38.520
when I was asked to do the
show, I said, this is perfect!

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:40.370
The bones are just
down the street.

00:34:40.370 --> 00:34:41.250
Booked the show.

00:34:41.250 --> 00:34:42.360
Signed the contract.

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:44.280
Discovered the
bones were a fraud.

00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:47.190
So this made for
interesting progress

00:34:47.190 --> 00:34:48.630
into telling the story.

00:34:48.630 --> 00:34:50.639
But that's the reason
it's set in a cemetery.

00:34:50.639 --> 00:34:52.530
The other thing is,
if you'll notice,

00:34:52.530 --> 00:34:55.650
using light and the
cemetery stones,

00:34:55.650 --> 00:34:58.650
the cemetery often disappears
to go into other worlds.

00:34:58.650 --> 00:35:00.270
And that we do with light.

00:35:00.270 --> 00:35:04.920
So my whole concept has been
go into the imagination when

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:07.540
you're going into these pieces.

00:35:07.540 --> 00:35:09.630
As opposed to,
let's be in a salon.

00:35:09.630 --> 00:35:10.800
And that's where we are.

00:35:10.800 --> 00:35:12.870
As opposed to,
let's be in a room.

00:35:12.870 --> 00:35:14.040
And that's where we are.

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:17.430
It's the ability to go to
as many places as possible

00:35:17.430 --> 00:35:20.040
with magic at the same time.

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:21.640
Another question.

00:35:21.640 --> 00:35:22.830
Gentleman over there.

00:35:22.830 --> 00:35:25.290
And then, maybe we'll have
a little music that relates

00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:28.410
to the question perhaps.

00:35:28.410 --> 00:35:30.920
AUDIENCE: So a little
bit different, I think.

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:35.970
But you mentioned that
combining music and theater

00:35:35.970 --> 00:35:37.977
has been a difficult craft.

00:35:37.977 --> 00:35:39.810
And a lot of people
dissuaded you from that.

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:41.435
So I was wondering
if you could tell us

00:35:41.435 --> 00:35:42.855
about any of your failures.

00:35:42.855 --> 00:35:44.070
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "FIFTH
 SYMPHONY"]

00:35:44.070 --> 00:35:45.090
HERSHEY FELDER:
Any of my failures?

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:47.640
Well, last night, I missed two
bars in "The Fifth Symphony."

00:35:47.640 --> 00:35:48.770
It was horrific.

00:35:48.770 --> 00:35:51.370
And I'm banging away
and bashing away.

00:35:51.370 --> 00:35:53.190
And let me see--

00:35:53.190 --> 00:35:53.780
where is it?

00:35:53.780 --> 00:35:55.148
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN,

00:35:55.148 --> 00:35:56.520
"FIFTH SYMPHONY"]

00:35:56.520 --> 00:35:57.960
And all of a
sudden, I said, why?

00:35:57.960 --> 00:35:59.910
What happened?

00:35:59.910 --> 00:36:02.440
What was going on was I was
thinking of the next line.

00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:04.440
Now, most of the audience,
if they didn't really

00:36:04.440 --> 00:36:06.106
know the piece
intimately, they wouldn't

00:36:06.106 --> 00:36:08.730
know that two bars a
little bit went sideways.

00:36:08.730 --> 00:36:10.650
But I was thinking
of the next line

00:36:10.650 --> 00:36:12.690
that was going to come
after I finished playing.

00:36:12.690 --> 00:36:14.010
And I put it in my head.

00:36:14.010 --> 00:36:15.390
And I'm doing this big passage.

00:36:15.390 --> 00:36:18.060
And I thought, oh my god,
where am I, all of a sudden.

00:36:18.060 --> 00:36:22.560
The concentration is so
specific and so razor sharp

00:36:22.560 --> 00:36:24.570
that even one move
in a wrong way,

00:36:24.570 --> 00:36:28.320
one physical move, one
wrong word, one anything,

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:30.060
sends me into the universe.

00:36:30.060 --> 00:36:32.316
And then panic strikes.

00:36:32.316 --> 00:36:33.690
And if you're
experienced enough,

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:36.960
you know how to bring yourself
back and to make that work

00:36:36.960 --> 00:36:38.910
and to figure your way out.

00:36:38.910 --> 00:36:42.060
But concentration
is to be so focused

00:36:42.060 --> 00:36:44.580
every second of
your being present

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:46.720
that even one hair of a--

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.260
so when failures--
most of the audience

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:50.880
wouldn't consider it a failure.

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:54.060
I get depressed
beyond all belief.

00:36:54.060 --> 00:36:55.710
I come home.

00:36:55.710 --> 00:36:58.710
I devour what's
ever in the fridge.

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:02.150
And then, I go out and I
find a Cheesecake Factory.

00:37:02.150 --> 00:37:05.820
And I mow through
that glass thing.

00:37:05.820 --> 00:37:08.100
And I mean, it's a
little bit like that.

00:37:08.100 --> 00:37:10.500
It's just because
you miss a passage.

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:12.900
Most of the audience
doesn't know.

00:37:12.900 --> 00:37:13.912
You miss a line.

00:37:13.912 --> 00:37:15.120
You want to get a beat on it.

00:37:15.120 --> 00:37:16.890
Or yesterday, it was
very interesting.

00:37:16.890 --> 00:37:20.640
Unfortunately, 7:30 shows
Tuesdays and Wednesdays--

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:21.960
they start a little bit early.

00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:24.450
So the traffic coming here
for there for Mountain View

00:37:24.450 --> 00:37:27.930
is horrific, especially
with all the birds nesting.

00:37:27.930 --> 00:37:30.420
People can't get
around, you know.

00:37:30.420 --> 00:37:32.910
So people were late.

00:37:32.910 --> 00:37:36.210
So as I'm beginning, flashlights
are going off, telephones.

00:37:36.210 --> 00:37:37.650
People are trying
to find things.

00:37:37.650 --> 00:37:39.100
And I'm talking directly to you.

00:37:39.100 --> 00:37:41.160
And I'm watching this go on.

00:37:41.160 --> 00:37:43.770
Fighting that kind
of concentration,

00:37:43.770 --> 00:37:47.100
fighting that kind of activity
around you, is torture.

00:37:47.100 --> 00:37:49.920
And so, the other night-- here
was something interesting.

00:37:49.920 --> 00:37:51.870
Here, we'll do a
piece for you, OK?

