00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:36.398
And worse, I'm looking at you.

00:41:36.398 --> 00:41:37.772
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:42.250
Well, this is good
story, perfect for here.

00:41:42.250 --> 00:41:44.940
So there I am at
the Geffen Theater.

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:45.440
Let me see.

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:47.180
What show what this was?

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:50.567
I think this was
"Gershwin," all right?

00:41:50.567 --> 00:41:52.400
So at some point, I
sing with the audience--

00:41:52.400 --> 00:41:54.275
[MUSIC - GEORGE GERSHWIN,
 "EMBRACEABLE YOU"]

00:41:54.275 --> 00:42:02.467
[SINGING]

00:42:02.467 --> 00:42:04.550
And then there's a question
period after the show,

00:42:04.550 --> 00:42:06.258
because people are
interested, like this.

00:42:06.258 --> 00:42:07.790
You know, that famous talk-back.

00:42:07.790 --> 00:42:10.580
So one guy is sitting
about halfway back.

00:42:10.580 --> 00:42:17.700
And he says, I just have to tell
you, I work at Skywalker Ranch.

00:42:17.700 --> 00:42:20.030
He says, I work for Lucasfilm.

00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:22.910
And he says, I've been
watching your shows.

00:42:22.910 --> 00:42:24.830
And I want to know
how you do it.

00:42:24.830 --> 00:42:27.240
I said, well, I practice a lot.

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:27.810
He says, no.

00:42:27.810 --> 00:42:29.990
I want to know
what the trick is.

00:42:29.990 --> 00:42:32.037
And I said, practice, really.

00:42:32.037 --> 00:42:32.870
And he says, no, no.

00:42:32.870 --> 00:42:33.980
I want to know the trick.

00:42:33.980 --> 00:42:37.160
Because you have
completely fooled me.

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:39.080
And he says, I do
this for a living.

00:42:39.080 --> 00:42:40.430
CGI is my thing.

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:42.350
I have worked on
the biggest films.

00:42:42.350 --> 00:42:44.570
I have directed--
how do you do it?

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:48.080
And I said, how do
I do what exactly?

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:51.200
He says, how do you match
your fingers exactly

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:51.920
to the recording?

00:42:51.920 --> 00:42:54.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:55.380 --> 00:42:56.270
And I looked at him.

00:42:56.270 --> 00:42:57.900
And I said, no, really.

00:42:57.900 --> 00:42:59.630
Ask that a-- he
says, how are you--

00:42:59.630 --> 00:43:03.320
he says, your fingers look-- we
have tried to do this in film

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:04.170
with getting this.

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:06.140
And we can't seem
to accomplish it.

00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:08.240
How do-- I said,
maybe hire a pianist.

00:43:08.240 --> 00:43:10.050
It will work.

00:43:10.050 --> 00:43:10.550
He says, no.

00:43:10.550 --> 00:43:11.630
But how do you do it?

00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:14.090
I said, you've got
to be kidding, right?

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:16.430
And he somehow couldn't
assess that the person who

00:43:16.430 --> 00:43:19.550
was talking to him and
singing to him, while playing

00:43:19.550 --> 00:43:22.220
in character, somehow
was that same person.

00:43:22.220 --> 00:43:24.369
So people have
asked how you do it.

00:43:24.369 --> 00:43:25.410
This is very interesting.

00:43:25.410 --> 00:43:26.705
Many of you know of Bach--

00:43:26.705 --> 00:43:29.180
[MUSIC - J.S. BACH]

00:43:35.620 --> 00:43:37.050
Next voice and so
on and so forth.

00:43:37.050 --> 00:43:39.760
So you have voices going
on in there, right?

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:43.060
The way I've structured
how to do this is this.

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:44.650
First, you must
learn the piano part.

00:43:44.650 --> 00:43:45.520
You must know the treble.

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:46.478
You must know the bass.

00:43:46.478 --> 00:43:48.670
You must know everything
inside the piano part.

00:43:48.670 --> 00:43:50.590
Then, you learn your text.

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:54.460
Then, you take the text, and
it needs to be placed exactly

00:43:54.460 --> 00:43:56.740
as another voice.

00:43:56.740 --> 00:43:58.480
Just like Bach, you
have all these voices

00:43:58.480 --> 00:43:59.920
going in counterpoint.

00:43:59.920 --> 00:44:01.690
So the voice that
I'm speaking actually

00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:04.270
becomes another
voice in the score.

00:44:04.270 --> 00:44:06.790
And it's placed exactly
at the right place.

00:44:06.790 --> 00:44:10.600
Then I have to give you
complete natural inflection.

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:13.390
So that, even though now I'm
acting to you as an actor

00:44:13.390 --> 00:44:16.930
or I'm talking to you, the
moment I go to the instrument,

00:44:16.930 --> 00:44:20.080
I have to somehow give the
illusion that the actor is

00:44:20.080 --> 00:44:21.730
still talking or the
character is still

00:44:21.730 --> 00:44:24.910
talking when, in effect, I have
turned a completely different

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:26.140
system on.

00:44:26.140 --> 00:44:28.300
And that system
is, the mechanism

00:44:28.300 --> 00:44:29.800
needs to work
automatically here,

00:44:29.800 --> 00:44:34.540
just as I did with that
Beethoven, with the sonata.

00:44:34.540 --> 00:44:35.990
And there's even worse ones.

00:44:35.990 --> 00:44:38.160
In the "Sonata
Pathetique"-- here.

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:39.868
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "SONATA
 PATHETIQUE"]

00:44:39.868 --> 00:44:43.460
(ACCENTED) C-minor--
notes packed together.

00:44:43.460 --> 00:44:45.860
A sound never before heard--

00:44:45.860 --> 00:44:48.130
moment.

00:44:48.130 --> 00:44:50.941
A funereal-like rhythm.

00:44:50.941 --> 00:44:54.050
(NORMAL SPEECH) It's
exactly in rhythm,

00:44:54.050 --> 00:44:56.060
the sense that something
is terribly wrong.

00:44:56.060 --> 00:44:58.540
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "SONATA
 PATHETIQUE"]

