It began with a
terrible pounding.

00:45:18.172 --> 00:45:19.660
(ROUGH PLAYING)

00:45:22.636 --> 00:45:34.770
Then, there was a
muffling of sound,

00:45:34.770 --> 00:45:37.635
an incessant ringing
and buzzing in the ears.

00:45:37.635 --> 00:45:55.860
[MUSIC - BEETHOVEN, "SONATA
 PATHETIQUE"]

00:45:55.860 --> 00:45:58.770
Something very
terrible was beginning

00:45:58.770 --> 00:46:00.090
to happen to his hearing.

00:46:02.740 --> 00:46:07.925
And the only thing he could
do was cry out in pain.

00:46:11.607 --> 00:46:13.740
(NORMAL SPEECH) And so,
everything is structured.

00:46:13.740 --> 00:46:17.260
Now, what is happening is,
I'm talking directly to you.

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:20.290
I looked at the keys only
when I absolutely needed to.

00:46:20.290 --> 00:46:23.390
But I'm talking to you
while I'm doing this.

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:25.000
So the sound is going on.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:27.550
This story is relating
to the color of sound.

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:29.870
In my eye, as I
am looking at you,

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:34.000
I am seeing the score of
Beethoven's page and the words

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.430
right exactly where
they need to be.

00:46:36.430 --> 00:46:40.510
But the craft I have developed
to such a degree, whereby

00:46:40.510 --> 00:46:43.600
I am giving you the illusion
that that person is actually

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:48.280
talking off the fly right then
and there about those notes.

00:46:48.280 --> 00:46:50.950
It has taken me 25 years
to figure out how to do it.

00:46:50.950 --> 00:46:53.680
And everybody who comes
says, oh, I play the piano.

00:46:53.680 --> 00:46:54.900
And I talk to the audience.

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:55.850
I'm going to do this.

00:46:55.850 --> 00:46:56.230
It's easy.

00:46:56.230 --> 00:46:56.650
It's fun.

00:46:56.650 --> 00:46:57.820
I said, yeah, give it a shot.

00:46:57.820 --> 00:46:58.262
Haha.

00:46:58.262 --> 00:46:58.761
Let's see.

00:46:58.761 --> 00:46:59.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:59.590 --> 00:47:01.340
Because it looks so simple.

00:47:01.340 --> 00:47:04.570
But again, in terms of
technology and understanding,

00:47:04.570 --> 00:47:07.720
it's finding the simplicity
in all this complexity

00:47:07.720 --> 00:47:12.190
and tearing away how
complex all of this is

00:47:12.190 --> 00:47:16.040
and making it direct, keeping
the illusion exactly as it is.

00:47:16.040 --> 00:47:17.920
And I still keep
fighting with that

00:47:17.920 --> 00:47:20.920
to try and make that even
better and better and better.

00:47:20.920 --> 00:47:22.910
But people talk about
inventing the form.

00:47:22.910 --> 00:47:24.520
So if I did, that's great.

00:47:24.520 --> 00:47:26.589
I hope people follow
along and do it

00:47:26.589 --> 00:47:27.880
and tell these kind of stories.

00:47:27.880 --> 00:47:28.963
Because they're important.

00:47:28.963 --> 00:47:30.790
And audiences want to hear them.

00:47:30.790 --> 00:47:33.790
And if I've learned anything
over all these years,

00:47:33.790 --> 00:47:37.020
it's that what engages
people above all--

00:47:37.020 --> 00:47:38.830
and I know you know this too--

00:47:38.830 --> 00:47:41.080
it's not the actual
technology, it's

00:47:41.080 --> 00:47:43.270
the story as it relates
to the technology,

00:47:43.270 --> 00:47:45.070
as it relates to the human.

00:47:45.070 --> 00:47:45.920
It's the story.

00:47:45.920 --> 00:47:47.050
It's the human story.

00:47:47.050 --> 00:47:48.760
And that's what makes
the difference, not

00:47:48.760 --> 00:47:52.990
the actual numbers and how they
jive to make something happen.

00:47:52.990 --> 00:47:54.730
Because ultimately,
what interconnects

00:47:54.730 --> 00:47:56.530
us are our stories.

00:47:56.530 --> 00:47:59.030
And if we don't have that,
then we're simply not human.

00:47:59.030 --> 00:48:01.580
So that's the interesting thing.

00:48:01.580 --> 00:48:04.750
And what I find interesting is
everybody said, oh, now we're

00:48:04.750 --> 00:48:06.160
going to have little screens.

00:48:06.160 --> 00:48:07.540
And people will be plugged in.

00:48:07.540 --> 00:48:09.820
And the whole world
will be in the screen.

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:12.970
The interesting thing is
what technology is developing

00:48:12.970 --> 00:48:14.920
is only our
enhancement of things.

00:48:14.920 --> 00:48:17.710
But people are running
back to the theater,

00:48:17.710 --> 00:48:20.020
because they need that
simple human interaction

00:48:20.020 --> 00:48:22.600
after a day of
technology, where we don't

00:48:22.600 --> 00:48:23.770
have that human interaction.

00:48:23.770 --> 00:48:25.520
And the other thing
that I've been talking

00:48:25.520 --> 00:48:27.460
about a lot as a
musician-- and I

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:30.130
don't know how you in this room
feel about it or how you work.

00:48:30.130 --> 00:48:33.495
But I've gone to a lot of
really wonderful great places

00:48:33.495 --> 00:48:35.620
where they develop a lot
of CGI stuff, I would say.

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:37.870
That's sort of my
involvement in Hollywood,

00:48:37.870 --> 00:48:40.100
is going to those
kinds of things,

00:48:40.100 --> 00:48:43.860
so taking what you develop
and then going to do that.

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:46.480
A lot of people are plugged in.

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:48.520
And they are listening
to the loudest things.

00:48:48.520 --> 00:48:50.230
And you walk through the rooms.

00:48:50.230 --> 00:48:52.270
And it's blaring.

00:48:52.270 --> 00:48:53.792
And I'm thinking,
the damage that

00:48:53.792 --> 00:48:55.000
must be doing to the hearing.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:56.458
I don't know if
you recognize this.

00:48:56.458 --> 00:48:59.260
But going now to a
movie or something,

00:48:59.260 --> 00:49:03.160
don't you think that it's so
much louder than it used to be?

00:49:03.160 --> 00:49:05.440
And what else
happens is we are now

00:49:05.440 --> 00:49:10.840
connecting emotional
reaction to decibel level.

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:11.650
But it's not.

00:49:11.650 --> 00:49:14.230
Emotional reaction is to
thinking and storytelling.

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:16.300
It's not amount of sound.

00:49:16.300 --> 00:49:18.340
And so I have
largely stayed away

00:49:18.340 --> 00:49:20.710
from plugging myself
in, going to loud clubs,

00:49:20.710 --> 00:49:21.780
and so on and so forth.

00:49:21.780 --> 00:49:23.680
Because here's with
lands up happening.

00:49:23.680 --> 00:49:26.220
People don't listen
to each other anymore.

00:49:26.220 --> 00:49:28.660
And that's how wars
begin and get worse,

00:49:28.660 --> 00:49:31.190
because you don't hear
what somebody is saying.

00:49:31.190 --> 00:49:34.570
And my biggest fear is that
talking in a room like this,

00:49:34.570 --> 00:49:38.020
people will not hear unless
they're being shouted at.

00:49:38.020 --> 00:49:41.170
And the emotional expression
is about being shouted.

00:49:41.170 --> 00:49:45.250
And what I've learned is, get
1,000, 10,000, 12,000, 100,000

00:49:45.250 --> 00:49:46.390
people in a room.

00:49:46.390 --> 00:49:48.430
Talk to them easily and quietly.

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:49.330
They will hear you.

00:49:49.330 --> 00:49:52.570
Scream at them, they'll
miss 90% of what you say.

00:49:52.570 --> 00:49:54.300
And it's a very
interesting thing.

00:49:54.300 --> 00:49:56.410
So the notion of young
people being plugged in

00:49:56.410 --> 00:49:58.501
from very early
on, their hearing

00:49:58.501 --> 00:49:59.500
is going to start to go.

00:49:59.500 --> 00:50:01.192
And this very much
so frightens me,

00:50:01.192 --> 00:50:02.650
in terms of the
state of the world.

00:50:02.650 --> 00:50:03.850
It's very simple.

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:06.137
But hearing is something
we need to maintain

00:50:06.137 --> 00:50:06.970
as much as possible.

00:50:06.970 --> 00:50:09.400
Beethoven is a prime example.

00:50:09.400 --> 00:50:11.652
And just a couple
last questions--

00:50:16.850 --> 00:50:18.705
AUDIENCE: Yeah, two questions.

00:50:18.705 --> 00:50:21.080
First of all, I should say,
I saw your show at the Center

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:22.640
for Performing Arts
on Sunday evening

00:50:22.640 --> 00:50:24.330
and thought it was
just really terrific--

00:50:24.330 --> 00:50:24.740
HERSHEY FELDER: Thank you.

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:25.340
AUDIENCE: --very entertaining.

00:50:25.340 --> 00:50:26.720
And I learned a lot
about Beethoven,

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:28.636
as a person, and his
relationship with his two

00:50:28.636 --> 00:50:31.940
younger brothers and his nephew
and how that kind of interacted

00:50:31.940 --> 00:50:33.820
with his music.

00:50:33.820 --> 00:50:35.570
As an innovator though,
innovators often

00:50:35.570 --> 00:50:37.010
get a lot of pushback.

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:40.370
They aren't always very well
appreciated and received.

00:50:40.370 --> 00:50:43.020
And Beethoven, I guess,
didn't really perform himself.

00:50:43.020 --> 00:50:45.540
He would have relied on
musicians and producers, sort

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:47.706
of the music industry, to
carry his music out there.

00:50:47.706 --> 00:50:48.660
HERSHEY FELDER: Mm-hm.

00:50:48.660 --> 00:50:50.035
AUDIENCE: I'm
wondering what kind

00:50:50.035 --> 00:50:52.151
of relationship and
reception he had at the time

00:50:52.151 --> 00:50:52.900
that he was alive.

00:50:52.900 --> 00:50:54.050
He's a superstar now.

00:50:54.050 --> 00:50:58.522
But was he a superstar while he
was alive and doing his music?

00:50:58.522 --> 00:51:00.980
HERSHEY FELDER: Was Beethoven
a superstar when he was alive

00:51:00.980 --> 00:51:02.104
and he was doing his music?

00:51:02.104 --> 00:51:04.460
To a degree, when he
was younger, absolutely.

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:06.082
And as he got deafer,
more certainly.

00:51:06.082 --> 00:51:07.790
And certainly, with
"The Ninth Symphony,"

00:51:07.790 --> 00:51:09.440
people loved him again.

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:11.644
He was the God of Music.

00:51:11.644 --> 00:51:12.560
There was no question.

00:51:12.560 --> 00:51:13.640
He was after Mozart.

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:14.720
And he was that.

00:51:14.720 --> 00:51:17.630
But as an individual, he
was sort of monstrous.

00:51:17.630 --> 00:51:19.634
And people said, at the
end of Beethoven's life,

00:51:19.634 --> 00:51:21.050
that he had totally
lost his mind.

00:51:21.050 --> 00:51:23.660
He was living in total squalor.

00:51:23.660 --> 00:51:25.910
There are stories about
people going to visit him.

00:51:25.910 --> 00:51:30.470
And I told one in this show
about how he had molding food

00:51:30.470 --> 00:51:31.520
all over the floor.

00:51:31.520 --> 00:51:33.410
His place was filthy.

00:51:33.410 --> 00:51:35.540
He didn't take care of anything.

00:51:35.540 --> 00:51:38.970
Rossini went to see him and said
there were leaks in the house.

00:51:38.970 --> 00:51:40.940
It was living in total squalor--

00:51:40.940 --> 00:51:42.920
the great Beethoven.

00:51:42.920 --> 00:51:46.910
And yet, at the
same time, he was

00:51:46.910 --> 00:51:51.350
recognized as being the
greatest musician of his time.

00:51:51.350 --> 00:51:53.060
But people had sort
of discarded him,

00:51:53.060 --> 00:51:55.010
as if he was just
a crazy old madman.

00:51:55.010 --> 00:51:57.920
He had lost all
sense of normalcy.

00:51:57.920 --> 00:51:58.430
He's deaf.

00:51:58.430 --> 00:51:59.630
He's nuts.

00:51:59.630 --> 00:52:02.476
And it's interesting that the
last bit of his life, people

00:52:02.476 --> 00:52:03.600
complained about his music.

00:52:03.600 --> 00:52:05.232
They said, it's
impossible to play.

00:52:05.232 --> 00:52:07.190
Certainly, as I talked
about "The Grosse Fuge,"

00:52:07.190 --> 00:52:09.350
and by that point,
the last years,

00:52:09.350 --> 00:52:12.440
people said that there is no
interest in any of his music.

00:52:12.440 --> 00:52:14.510
It's just the rantings
of a crazy man.

00:52:14.510 --> 00:52:17.600
Today we look at it as being the
greatest advancement probably

00:52:17.600 --> 00:52:20.030
in the history of Western music.

00:52:20.030 --> 00:52:20.870
You know?

00:52:20.870 --> 00:52:22.250
And that's another thing.

00:52:22.250 --> 00:52:22.910
He faced that.

00:52:22.910 --> 00:52:27.020
And he did say this,
when the little boy says,

00:52:27.020 --> 00:52:30.290
nobody understood my piece,
he actually responded.

00:52:30.290 --> 00:52:32.000
Oh, don't look so sad, my boy.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:33.710
One day, they will
understand it.

00:52:33.710 --> 00:52:36.680
They are just too stupid
to at this point--

00:52:36.680 --> 00:52:39.390
something like that.

00:52:39.390 --> 00:52:42.410
But that goes for anybody who's
going to push the envelope,

00:52:42.410 --> 00:52:43.760
doesn't it?

00:52:43.760 --> 00:52:46.430
And every time I
get a lousy review--

00:52:46.430 --> 00:52:49.010
they're happening less and
less, which is scaring me.

00:52:49.010 --> 00:52:50.120
And here's why.

00:52:50.120 --> 00:52:52.190
When you get a good
review, you think,

00:52:52.190 --> 00:52:53.300
people are getting it now.

00:52:53.300 --> 00:52:54.810
They're not going to
get it in 100 years.

00:52:54.810 --> 00:52:56.226
They're going to
think it's trash.

00:52:56.226 --> 00:52:58.632
So my view is, the
worse the review is now,

00:52:58.632 --> 00:53:00.590
the better off you're
going to be in 100 years.

00:53:00.590 --> 00:53:01.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:01.640 --> 00:53:04.160
So that's when you hold
up all your lousy reviews.

00:53:04.160 --> 00:53:06.260
And everybody says,
this is sa-da-da-da-da.

00:53:06.260 --> 00:53:07.670
And you say, well, no.

00:53:07.670 --> 00:53:08.390
I know.

00:53:08.390 --> 00:53:11.580
And maybe, in 100 years,
it will be worth something.

00:53:11.580 --> 00:53:14.360
But I think, anybody
who has something new

00:53:14.360 --> 00:53:18.920
and something different
to say will eventually

00:53:18.920 --> 00:53:20.930
encounter that to some degree.

00:53:20.930 --> 00:53:22.400
His was a different problem.

00:53:22.400 --> 00:53:23.180
He was deaf.

00:53:23.180 --> 00:53:25.400
And so he had to live with that.

00:53:25.400 --> 00:53:28.670
And before I do just
this last little piece--

00:53:28.670 --> 00:53:31.831
and I do want to thank Steinway
for sending us this piano.

00:53:31.831 --> 00:53:33.830
Because otherwise, there
would be no music here.

00:53:33.830 --> 00:53:38.600
Although, why is there no
piano permanently here?

00:53:38.600 --> 00:53:39.990
Yes, there needs to be one.

00:53:39.990 --> 00:53:40.940
That's another thing.

00:53:40.940 --> 00:53:44.490
Having a piano somewhere
is very important.

00:53:44.490 --> 00:53:46.790
My wife used to say, every
time I go into a house

00:53:46.790 --> 00:53:48.800
without a piano, I
get very nervous.

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:50.360
I wonder about the people.

00:53:50.360 --> 00:53:51.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:52.590 --> 00:53:54.860
And so, it's like
meeting people with dogs.

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:55.970
People with dogs are OK.

00:53:55.970 --> 00:53:58.960
People without dogs, you
have to ask a question.

00:53:58.960 --> 00:54:03.050
So Steinway has been
wonderful in supporting me

00:54:03.050 --> 00:54:05.720
for all these years,
by sending pianos

00:54:05.720 --> 00:54:07.160
wherever they are needed.

00:54:07.160 --> 00:54:10.110
And it's really a marvelous,
marvelous organization.

00:54:10.110 --> 00:54:13.320
And it's location all
around the world--

00:54:13.320 --> 00:54:14.450
they take care of pianists.

00:54:14.450 --> 00:54:15.380
And they take care of us.

00:54:15.380 --> 00:54:16.840
And hence, we can
bring you music.

00:54:16.840 --> 00:54:19.550
So thank you the
folks at Steinway.

00:54:19.550 --> 00:54:23.540
Before this last
piece, Beethoven--

00:54:23.540 --> 00:54:27.710
I think of what he said
when he was 31-years-old.

00:54:27.710 --> 00:54:31.720
It was a letter he
wrote to his brothers.

00:54:31.720 --> 00:54:33.620
He was 31.

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:35.200
And it's 25 years
before he died.

00:54:35.200 --> 00:54:37.783
And there's still an argument
as to whether he sent the letter

00:54:37.783 --> 00:54:40.040
and he got it back or he
never sent the letter at all.

00:54:40.040 --> 00:54:43.870
But it was in his desk
at the end of his life.

00:54:43.870 --> 00:54:45.410
And it went like this.

00:54:45.410 --> 00:54:47.800
And the first time I read
it, it broke my heart.

00:54:47.800 --> 00:54:50.217
Think of this-- 31-years-old.

00:54:50.217 --> 00:54:51.550
And I'll do it in his character.

00:54:51.550 --> 00:54:55.430
(GERMAN ACCENT) Oh,
you men who declare

00:54:55.430 --> 00:54:59.060
me to be malevolent,
stubborn, and misanthropic,

00:54:59.060 --> 00:55:02.450
how gravely you wrong me.

00:55:02.450 --> 00:55:08.450
For you do not know the secret
cause behind the appearance.

00:55:08.450 --> 00:55:12.890
Ever since childhood
onward, my art and my mind

00:55:12.890 --> 00:55:16.370
have tended towards
a gentle benevolence.

00:55:16.370 --> 00:55:21.590
But for the past six years,
since my 26th birthday,

00:55:21.590 --> 00:55:26.240
I have been suffering from
an incurable affliction, only

00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:30.470
aggravated by stupid physicians.

00:55:30.470 --> 00:55:34.340
Year after year, I am deceived
of the hope of an improvement.

00:55:34.340 --> 00:55:36.740
And I am now forced
to contemplate

00:55:36.740 --> 00:55:42.610
the prospect of an illness
that shall never be cured.

00:55:42.610 --> 00:55:45.940
Well then, how can
I possibly admit

00:55:45.940 --> 00:55:50.060
to being defective in
the very sense which

00:55:50.060 --> 00:55:54.760
had been more highly developed
in me than in other men?

00:55:54.760 --> 00:55:57.760
A sense which I had
at once possessed

00:55:57.760 --> 00:56:01.380
in its most perfect form?

00:56:01.380 --> 00:56:07.070
So please, forgive me if
I appear to be difficult.

00:56:07.070 --> 00:56:08.770
But what am I to do?

00:56:08.770 --> 00:56:12.736
Am I to venture out to
a social gathering--

00:56:12.736 --> 00:56:17.490
hm?-- only to say, speak up!

00:56:17.490 --> 00:56:21.393
I cannot hear you!

00:56:21.393 --> 00:56:23.838
I am deaf!

00:56:28.728 --> 00:56:31.510
And because of this,
I have seriously

00:56:31.510 --> 00:56:34.270
considered taking my own life.

00:56:37.400 --> 00:56:39.970
But each time I decide,
in the end, my need

00:56:39.970 --> 00:56:43.090
for my art returns.

00:56:43.090 --> 00:56:47.050
And now, this is the only
thing that shall keep me alive.

00:56:47.050 --> 00:56:48.820
Death shall now
come as he pleases.

00:56:48.820 --> 00:56:51.880
For no longer
shall I invite him.

00:56:51.880 --> 00:56:55.270
And when he does come,
bravely, I shall come out.

00:56:55.270 --> 00:56:58.890
And I shall accept my fate.

00:56:58.890 --> 00:57:02.640
And when this day happens,
I ask of you only one thing.

00:57:05.937 --> 00:57:12.115
Please, do not forget me.

00:57:15.030 --> 00:57:17.940
